%I A394514 #8 Apr 09 2026 09:54:58
%S A394514 1,2,4,6,3,9,12,8,10,5,15,18,14,16,20,22,11,33,21,30,24,28,7,35,25,40,
%T A394514 26,39,13,52,32,50,34,48,27,45,36,44,38,42,46,23,69,51,68,17,85,55,80,
%U A394514 54,78,56,77,49,70,58,66,57,63,60,62,31,93,72,92,64,90,65
%N A394514 a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2; for n > 2, a(n) is the greatest unused number less than a(n-2) that shares a factor with a(n-1), else, if no such number exists, a(n) is the smallest unused number greater than a(n-2) that shares a factor with a(n-1).
%C A394514 The sequence uses a similar method to A386482 for choosing a(n) except here a(n) is chosen to be less than a(n-2), if possible, rather than a(n-1). Like that sequence, the primes do not occur in their natural order, and a prime can be preceded and followed by terms that are high multiples of the prime.
%C A394514 There is a concentration of terms along a line with a gradient ~0.86, although many other terms exist both above and below this line, with terms above the line showing some clustering for many values.
%C A394514 The fixed points in the first 10^6 terms are 1, 2, 8, 25, 60, 74, 99, 714, 7424, and 149157, although more likely exist. The sequence is conjectured to be a permutation of the positive numbers.
%H A394514 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394514/b394514.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A394514 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394514/a394514.png">Image of the first 10^6 terms</a>. The green line is a(n) = n.
%e A394514 a(8) = 8 as 8 is unused, is less than a(8-2) = a(6) = 9, and it shares a factor with a(8-1) = a(7) = 12. This is the first term to differ from A386482.
%Y A394514 Cf. A386482, A064413, A387231, A384045.
